## Answer

For the `SET` command specifically (as opposed to `GET`, `APPEND`, `INCR`, etc. which each have their own `checkType()` call), the WRONGTYPE reply is constructed in one place, reached from `setGenericCommand()` in `src/t_string.c` via two possible paths depending on the options used in the `SET` call:

**1. `SET key value GET` (the `GET` option)**
`setGenericCommand()` (src/t_string.c:87) calls `getGenericCommand(c)` at line 100 when `OBJ_SET_GET` is set. Inside `getGenericCommand()` (src/t_string.c:461-473), the type check happens at:
```
src/t_string.c:467   if (checkType(c,o,OBJ_STRING)) {
src/t_string.c:468       return C_ERR;
src/t_string.c:469   }
```

**2. `SET key value IFEQ/IFNE/IFDEQ/IFDNE ...` (conditional-set variants)**
`setGenericCommand()` checks the type of the existing key directly:
```
src/t_string.c:118   kvobj *current = lookupKeyRead(c->db, key);
src/t_string.c:119   if (checkType(c, current, OBJ_STRING)) {
src/t_string.c:120       return;
src/t_string.c:121   }
```

Both call the shared helper `checkType()`, which is where the actual error reply object is built and sent:

```
src/object.c:884  int checkType(client *c, robj *o, int type) {
src/object.c:885      /* A NULL is considered an empty key */
src/object.c:886      if (o && o->type != type) {
src/object.c:887          addReplyErrorObject(c,shared.wrongtypeerr);
src/object.c:888          return 1;
src/object.c:889      }
src/object.c:890      return 0;
src/object.c:891  }
```

The reply text itself (`shared.wrongtypeerr`) is a preallocated shared object initialized once at server startup:
```
src/server.c:2203  shared.wrongtypeerr = createObject(OBJ_STRING,sdsnew(
src/server.c:2204      "-WRONGTYPE Operation against a key holding the wrong kind of value\r\n"));
```

**Important note on plain `SET`:** A bare `SET key value` on an existing key of a different type does **not** trigger this error â€” Redis's plain SET unconditionally overwrites the key regardless of its current type. WRONGTYPE only surfaces in the SET path when the `GET` option is used (because it must read back the old string value) or when one of the `IFEQ/IFNE/IFDEQ/IFDNE` compare-and-set variants is used (because it must read and compare the old value).

**Method:** Used `grep` to locate `checkType`/`WRONGTYPE` occurrences in `t_string.c`, then `LSP prepareCallHierarchy` + `incomingCalls` on `checkType` (src/object.c:884) to enumerate all 115 call sites across the codebase and confirm that within `t_string.c` only `setGenericCommand` (line 119) and `getGenericCommand` (line 467, reached from `setGenericCommand` line 100) are in the SET path â€” all other callers there (`appendCommand`, `getexCommand`, `incrDecrCommand`, etc.) belong to different commands.
